,Not Recommended,235250,33684805,Posted: 20 July,all,Audion: King of Antics,"SSTD is held back by a failure to focus on the backbone behind the gameplay. The window doesn't let you resize. This means the cutesy pixel graphics scale horribly and all the pixels become different sizes. The options in general for this game seem pathetic. Anti Aliasing, hotkeys, and music choice seem to be the extent. They do use the default windows combination for fullscreen rather than set it as an option. There's no choice to lock the mouse to the game either, which means you can overdo a movement and your camera flies off the screen.  This also causes the map to fight against you when you try to select a map. The actual gameplay is pretty okay, if a bit vague at times (For example, trying to upgrade a tower with insufficient funds only states that the tower is not a ""valid target"") and the idea of particpating in the attack phase has been applied here as well. It does feel extremely slow in the beginning because this game follows the route of Sanctum 2 and requires you to play the game before you unlock more slots. Which would be okay if it wasn't for the that fast that unlike Sanctum 2, those slots are your ONLY way to interact with the attack wave, rather than FPS gameplay with no artificial downtime.I dunno man, it's only 4 bucks or less. It's not a bad game either, just marred by poor settings menu and ugly pixel scaling."
